Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch-thick wedges. Trim and thinly slice @button mushrooms{8%ounce} (skip if your mushrooms are pre-sliced!). Halve, peel, and thinly slice @yellow onion{1}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @mayonnaise{2%tablespoon} with @garlic powder{1/4%tsp}; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. (You'll use the rest of the garlic powder in the next step.)

> Save potatoes for another use.

Trim and discard woody bottom ends from @asparagus{6%ounce}.

Toss potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with remaining @garlic powder{3/4%tsp}, a drizzle of @cooking oil{4%teaspoon}, salt, and pepper.

Roast on top rack until browned and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

> Swap in asparagus for potatoes; roast until lightly browned and tender, 10-12 minutes.

Meanwhile, heat a large drizzle of oil in a large #pan{} over medium-high heat. Add mushrooms and season with salt and pepper. Cook, stirring, until lightly browned, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> TIP: Lower heat and add a splash of water if mushrooms begin to brown too quickly.

Add onion and another drizzle of oil; season with salt and pepper. Cook, stirring, until veggies are browned and tender, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Stir in @mushroom stock concentrate{1} and @water{2%tablespoon}; cook until water has evaporated and mixture is jammy.

Turn off heat; remove from pan and set aside. Wash out pan.

Spread half the @sourdough bread{4%slice} with @Dijon mustard{2%teaspoon}, then top with even layers of @Swiss cheese{4%slice} (tearing to fit if necessary), mushrooms and onion, and @Monterey Jack cheese{1/4%cup}.

Top with remaining sourdough slices to create sandwiches.

Melt @butter{1%tablespoon} in pan used for mushrooms and onion over medium heat. Add sandwiches and push around in pan until melted butter has absorbed. Cook until bread is golden brown and cheese is slightly melted, ~{4-6%minutes}.

> TIP: If you have a heavy-bottomed pan, place on top of the sandwiches as they cook for a real panini experience!

Add another @butter{1%tablespoon} to pan, then flip sandwiches and push around again until melted butter has absorbed. Cook until bread is golden brown and cheese melts, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Halve panini on a diagonal and divide between plates. Serve with potato wedges and garlic aioli on the side for dipping.